<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>The Analysis of Knowledge</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Tue Feb 6, 2001; substantive revision Wed Jan 21, 2026</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
For any person, there are some things they know, and some things they
don&rsquo;t. What exactly is the difference? What does it take to know
something? It&rsquo;s not enough just to believe it&mdash;we
don&rsquo;t know the things we&rsquo;re wrong about. Knowledge seems
to be more like a way of getting at the truth. The analysis of
knowledge concerns the attempt to articulate in what exactly this kind
of &ldquo;getting at the truth&rdquo; consists.</p>

<p>
More particularly, the project of analysing knowledge is to state
conditions that are individually necessary and jointly sufficient for
propositional knowledge, thoroughly answering the question:
&ldquo;What does it take to know something?&rdquo; By
&ldquo;propositional knowledge&rdquo;, we mean knowing <em>that
something is the case</em>, i.e., knowledge of a proposition. For
example, if Susan knows that Alyssa is a musician, she has knowledge
of the proposition that Alyssa is a musician. Propositional knowledge
should be distinguished from knowledge by &ldquo;acquaintance&rdquo;,
for example when we say that Susan knows <em>Alyssa</em>, or that she
knows <em>Vancouver</em>. (Knowing Susan may involve knowing some
propositions about Susan, but it is only the latter kind of knowledge
that is our focus here.)</p>

<p>
&ldquo;Knows that&rdquo; is the canonical English expression for
indicating propositional knowledge. We also often attribute
propositional knowledge with so-called &ldquo;knows-wh&rdquo;
locutions: Sooyung might know whether the shop is open, for instance,
or Juan might know who won the election. These cases also involve
propositional knowledge: one knows these things by knowing the
proposition that is the answer to the embedded question. Sooyung can
know whether the shop is open by knowing that the shop is not open.
There is some controversy over the particular status of knowledge-how
(i.e., &ldquo;Ahmed knows how to ride a bicycle&rdquo;)&mdash;see
Stanley 2011 and his opponents discussed therein.</p>

<p>
The propositional knowledge that is the analysandum of the analysis of
knowledge literature is paradigmatically expressed in English by
sentences of the form &ldquo;<em>S</em> knows that <em>P</em>&rdquo;,
where &ldquo;<em>S</em>&rdquo; refers to the knowing subject, and
&ldquo;<em>P</em>&rdquo; expresses the proposition that is known. A
proposed analysis consists of a statement of the following form:
&ldquo;<em>S</em> knows that <em>P</em> if and only if
<em>J</em>,&rdquo; where <em>J</em> indicates
that <em>S</em> satisfies
the analysans&mdash;paradigmatically, a list of conditions that
are individually necessary and jointly sufficient for <em>S</em> to
have knowledge that <em>P</em>.</p>

<p>
It is not enough merely to pick out the actual extension of knowledge.
Even if, in actual fact, all cases of <em>S</em> knowing that
<em>P</em> are cases in which
<em>S</em> satisfies <em>J</em>, and all cases of the latter
are cases of the former, <em>J</em> might fail as an analysis of
knowledge. For example, it might be that there are possible cases of
knowledge without <em>J</em>, or vice versa. A proper analysis of
knowledge should at least be a necessary truth. Consequently,
hypothetical thought experiments provide appropriate test cases for
various analyses, as we shall see below.</p>

<p>
Even a necessary biconditional linking knowledge to some state
<em>J</em> would probably not be sufficient for an analysis of
knowledge, although just what more is required is a matter of some
controversy. According to one version of the project, to analyze
knowledge is literally to identify the components that make up
knowledge&mdash;compare a chemist who analyzes a sample to learn its
chemical composition. On this interpretation of the project of
analyzing knowledge, the defender of a successful analysis of
knowledge will be committed to something like the metaphysical claim
that <em>what it is</em> for <em>S</em> to know that <em>P</em>
is for some list of conditions involving <em>S</em> and the
proposition that <em>P</em> to obtain. Other theorists think of
the analysis of knowledge as distinctively
<em>conceptual</em>&mdash;to analyse knowledge is to limn the
structure of the <em>concept</em> of knowledge. On one version of this
approach, the concept <em>knowledge</em> is literally composed of more
basic concepts, linked together by something like Boolean operators.
Some contributors to the literature write in terms of
<em>definitions</em> of knowledge. Consequently, an analysis is
subject not only to extensional accuracy, but to facts about the
cognitive representation of knowledge and other epistemic notions. In
practice, many epistemologists engaging in the project of analyzing
knowledge leave these metaphilosophical interpretive questions
unresolved; attempted analyses, and counterexamples thereto, are often
proposed without its being made explicit whether the claims are
intended as metaphysical or conceptual
 ones.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-1" id="ref-1">1</a>]</sup>
 In many cases, this lack of specificity may be legitimate, since all
parties tend to agree that an analysis of knowledge ought <em>at
least</em> to be extensionally correct in all metaphysically possible
worlds. As we shall see, many theories have been defended and,
especially, refuted on those terms.</p>

<p>
The attempt to analyze knowledge has received a considerable amount of
attention from epistemologists, particularly in the late
20<sup>th</sup> century, but no analysis has been widely accepted.
Some contemporary epistemologists reject the assumption that knowledge
is susceptible to analysis.</p>
</div> 

