<li>Lewis, David K., 1973, <em>Counterfactuals</em>, Cambridge, MA:
Harvard University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1996, &ldquo;Elusive Knowledge&rdquo;,
<em>Australasian Journal of Philosophy</em>, 74(4): 549&ndash;567.
doi:10.1080/00048409612347521</li>

<li>Littlejohn, Clayton, 2012, <em>Justification and the
Truth-Connection</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Lowy, Catherine, 1978, &ldquo;Gettier&rsquo;s Notion of
Justification&rdquo;, <em>Mind</em>, 87(345): 105&ndash;108.
doi:10.1093/mind/LXXXVII.1.105</li>

<li>Lyons, Jack C., 2009, <em>Perception and Basic Beliefs: Zombies,
Modules and the Problem of the External World</em>, New York: Oxford
University Press. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195373578.001.0001</li>

<li>McGlynn, Aidan, 2014, <em>Knowledge First?</em>, Basingstoke:
Palgrave. doi:10.1057/9781137026460</li>

<li>McKinnon, Rachel, 2013, &ldquo;Getting Luck Properly under
Control&rdquo;, <em>Metaphilosophy</em>, 44(4): 496&ndash;511.
doi:10.1111/meta.12044</li>

<li>Merricks, Trenton, 1995, &ldquo;Warrant Entails Truth&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy and Phenomenological Research</em>, 55(4):
841&ndash;855. doi:10.2307/2108335</li>

<li>Miracchi, Lisa, 2015, &ldquo;Competence to Know&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 172(1): 29&ndash;56.
doi:10.1007/s11098-014-0325-9</li>

<li>Myers-Schulz, Blake, and Eric Schwitzgebel, 2013,
&ldquo;Knowing That <em>P</em> without Believing That
<em>P</em>&rdquo;, <em>No&ucirc;s</em>, 47(2): 371&ndash;384.
doi:10.1111/nous.12022</li>

<li>Nagel, Jennifer, 2010, &ldquo;Epistemic Anxiety and Adaptive
Invariantism&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Perspectives</em>, 24(1):
407&ndash;435. doi:10.1111/j.1520-8583.2010.00198.x</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;Knowledge as a Mental
State&rdquo;, <em>Oxford Studies in Epistemology</em>, 4:
275&ndash;310. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199672707.003.0010</li>

<li>Navarro, Jes&uacute;s, 2023, &ldquo;Epistemic Luck and Epistemic
Risk&rdquo;, <em>Erkenntnis</em>, 88(3): 929&ndash;950. doi:
10.1007/s10670-021-00387-9</li>

<li>Neta, Ram &amp; Rohrbaugh, Guy, 2004, &ldquo;Luminosity
and the Safety of Knowledge,&rdquo; <em>Pacific Philosophical
Quarterly</em>, 85: 396&ndash;406.
doi: 10.1111/j.1468-0114.2004.00207.x</li>

<li>Nozick, Robert, 1981, <em>Philosophical Explanations</em>,
Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press.</li>

<li>Owens, David, 2000, <em>Reason without Freedom: The Problem of
Epistemic Normativity</em>, London: Routledge.</li>

<li>Pappas, George, &ldquo;Internalist vs. Externalist Conceptions of
Epistemic Justification&rdquo;, <em>The Stanford Encyclopedia of
Philosophy</em> (Spring 2023 Edition), Edward N. Zalta &amp; Uri
Nodelman (eds.), URL =
&lt;https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2023/entries/justep-intext/&gt;.</li>

<li>Phillips, Stephen H., and N.S. Ramanuja Tatacharya (trans.), 2004,
<em>Epistemology of Perception: Ga&#7749;ge&#347;a&rsquo;s
&ldquo;Tattvacint&#257;ma&#7751;i&rdquo;</em>, New York: American
Institute of Buddhist Studies.</li>

<li>Plantinga, Alvin, 1993, <em>Warrant and Proper Function</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press. doi:10.1093/0195078640.001.0001</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1996, &ldquo;Respondeo&rdquo;, in Jonathan
L. Kvanvig (ed.), <em>Warrant in Contemporary Epistemology.  Essays in
Honor of Plantinga&rsquo;s Theory of Knowledge</em>, Lanham, MD:
Rowman and Littlefield, pp. 307&ndash;378.</li>

<li>Pollock, John J., 1986, <em>Contemporary Theories of
Knowledge</em>, Totowa, NJ: Rowman and Littlefield.</li>

<li>Pritchard, Duncan, 2005, <em>Epistemic Luck</em>, New York: Oxford
University Press. doi:10.1093/019928038X.001.0001</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, &ldquo;Epistemic Risk&rdquo;,
<em>Journal of Philosophy</em>, 113(11): 550&ndash;571.
doi:10.5840/jphil20161131137</li>

<li>Pritchard, Duncan, Alan Millar, and Adrian Haddock, 2010,
<em>The Nature and Value of Knowledge: Three Investigations</em>, New
York: Oxford University Press.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199586264.001.0001</li>

<li>Radford, Colin, 1966, &ldquo;Knowledge&mdash;By Examples&rdquo;,
<em>Analysis</em>, 27(1): 1&ndash;11. doi:10.2307/3326979</li>

<li>Rose, David, and Jonathan Schaffer, 2013, &ldquo;Knowledge
Entails Dispositional Belief&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Studies</em>,
166(Supplement 1): 19&ndash;50. doi:10.1007/s11098-012-0052-z</li>

<li>Roush, Sherrilyn, 2005, <em>Tracking Truth: Knowledge, Evidence,
and Science</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012, &ldquo;Sensitivity and
Closure,&rdquo; in Kelly Becker and Tim Black (eds.), <em>The
Sensitivity Principle in Epistemology</em>, New York: Cambridge
University Press, pp. 242&ndash;268</li>

<li>Russell, Bertrand, 1923, <em>Human Knowledge: Its Scope and
Limits</em>, London: George Allen and Unwin Ltd.</li>

<li>Rysiew, Patrick, 2001, &ldquo;The Context-Sensitivity of Knowledge
Attributions&rdquo;, <em>No&ucirc;s</em>, 35(4): 477&ndash;514.
doi:10.1111/0029-4624.00349</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2023, &ldquo;Epistemic
Contextualism&rdquo;, <em>The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</em>
(Winter 2023 Edition), Edward N. Zalta and Uri Nodelman (eds.), URL =
&lt;https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2023/entries/contextualism-epistemology/&gt;.</li>

<li>Schaffer, Jonathan, 2004, &ldquo;From Contextualism to
Contrastivism&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 119(1&ndash;2):
73&ndash;104. doi:10.1023/B:PHIL.0000029351.56460.8c</li>

<li>Schiffer, Stephen, 1996, &ldquo;Contextualist Solutions to
Scepticism&rdquo;, <em>Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society</em>,
96(1): 317&ndash;333. doi:10.1093/aristotelian/96.1.317</li>

<li>Schulz, Moritz, 2021, &ldquo;Strong Knowledge, Weak
Belief?&rdquo;, <em>Synthese</em>, 199(3&ndash;4): 8741&ndash;8753.
doi:10.1007/s11229-021-03180-x</li>

<li>Shope, Robert K., 1983, <em>The Analysis of Knowing: A Decade of
Research</em>, Princeton: Princeton University Press.</li>

<li>Siscoe, Robert Weston, 2021, &ldquo;Belief, Rational and
Justified&rdquo;, <em>Mind</em>, 130(517): 59&ndash;83.
doi:10.1093/mind/fzaa021</li>

<li>Sosa, Ernest, 1999, &ldquo;How to Defeat Opposition to
Moore&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Perspectives</em>, 13: 141&ndash;153.
doi:10.1111/0029-4624.33.s13.7</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2007, <em>A Virtue Epistemology: Apt Belief
and Reflective Knowledge</em> (Volume I), New York: Oxford University
Press. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199297023.001.0001</li>

<li>Stanley, Jason, 2005, <em>Knowledge and Practical Interests</em>,
New York: Oxford University Press.
doi:10.1093/0199288038.001.0001</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011, <em>Know How</em>, New York: Oxford
University Press. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199695362.001.0001</li>

<li>Steglich-Petersen, Asbj&oslash;rn, 2010, &ldquo;Luck as an
Epistemic Notion&rdquo;, <em>Synthese</em>, 176 (3): 361&ndash;377.
doi:10.1007/s11229-009-9569-x</li>

<li>Stine, G.C., 1976, &ldquo;Skepticism, Relevant Alternatives, and
Deductive Closure&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 29(4):
249&ndash;261. doi:10.1007/BF00411885</li>

<li>Sturgeon, Scott, 1993, &ldquo;The Gettier Problem&rdquo;,
<em>Analysis</em>, 53(3): 156&ndash;164. doi:10.2307/3328464</li>

<li>Sutton, Jonathan, 2007, <em>Without Justification</em>, Cambridge,
MA: The MIT Press.</li>

<li>Unger, Peter, 1968, &ldquo;An Analysis of Factual
Knowledge&rdquo;, <em>Journal of Philosophy</em>, 65(6):
157&ndash;170. doi:10.2307/2024203</li>

<li>Weatherson, Brian, 2012, &ldquo;Knowledge, Bets, and
Interests&rdquo;, in Jessica Brown and Mikkel Gerken
(eds.), <em>Knowledge Ascriptions</em>, New York: Oxford
University Press, pp. 75&ndash;103.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199693702.003.0004</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2024, <em>Knowledge: A Human Interest
Story</em>, Open Book Publishers.</li>

<li>Williamson, Timothy, 2000, <em>Knowledge and Its Limits</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press. doi:10.1093/019925656X.001.0001</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2005, &ldquo;Knowledge, Context, and the
Agent&rsquo;s Point of View&rdquo;, in Gerhard Preyer and Georg
Peter (eds.), <em>Contextualism in Philosophy: Knowledge, Meaning, and
Truth</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press,
pp. 91&ndash;114.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2009, &ldquo;Reply to Alvin Goldman&rdquo;,
in Greenough &amp; Pritchard 2009, pp. 305&ndash;312.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199287512.003.0017</li>

<li>Worsnip, Alex, 2017, &ldquo;Contextualism and Knowledge
Norms&rdquo;, in Ichikawa 2017-b, pp. 177-189.</li>

<li>Wright, Crispin, 2004, &ldquo;Warrant for Nothing (And Foundations
for Free)?&rdquo; <em>Aristotelian Society Supplementary Volume</em>,
78(1): 167&ndash;212. doi:10.1111/j.0309-7013.2004.00121.x</li>

<li>Zagzebski, Linda, 1994, &ldquo;The Inescapability of Gettier
Problems&rdquo;, <em>The Philosophical Quarterly</em>, 44(174):
65&ndash;73. doi:10.2307/2220147</li>
</ul>
</div> 

